review: Easy recipe, but needed a bit more flavor. I will add garlic, paprika, and cumin next time.

name: slow cooker beef short ribs
review: Very good, super easy. It's a really tangy sauce from the vinegar, which I liked.

name: sun dried tomato bruschetta with goat cheese
review: SO good! I ate 4 of them fresh from the oven!

name: injera  ethiopian flat bread
review: Wonderful flavor, perfect with the chicken.

name: best ever roasted pumpkin seeds
review: We really liked these. The Worcestershire sauce added a unique taste. Our family didn't agree that these were the "Best Ever" and they won't replace our favorite recipe. But, they were really good!

name: black bean and garbanzo salad
review: We loved this simple, yet tasty salad. The fact that it is healthy too, is an added bonus. When I started to make this, I realized I didn't have garbanzo beans, so I used cannellini beans instead. Also, I added: some sugar to cut the tart of the lime juice, cumin, black pepper, and additional salt. It was even better the next day. Thank you for sharing! **Made for 2017 Football Pool**

name: rootin  tooin  sweet   sassy sauce
review: This recipe was made on 11/28/17 for a Cook A Thon to honor Susie D.. i had to make a couple of substitutions. Instead of using the fresh garlic & ginger ,I used 1 teaspoon of dried ginger powder and 1 teaspoon of dried garlic powder was used.I do think however, the next time this is made I'm going to cut back a bit on the vinegar. It was very good but I think instead of using it the same it was made, I'll make it a day or two before needed it, so the flavors will have time to meld for a richer flavor. Susie D,you will be greatly missed,and every time I make this I'll think of you. " Keep Smiling :) "

name: my best chicken and rice in wine
review: I followed the directions and only used the ingredients listed. I anticipated something rich and flavorful considering the butter, wine, garlic and onions and the rice soaking up all that goodness. Instead, it seemed to lack flavor and was only deemed "okay" by my family. If I mde this again I would definitely season my chicken before browning and probably experiment a little with additional ingredients as most of the other reviewers did.

name: pumpkin pie seeds
review: I didn't have high expectations because I usually prefer savory over sweet when it comes to seeds and nuts. However, I was surprised at how much I enjoyed them. I'm not even a pumpkin pie fan, but these sunflower seeds were pretty tasty.

name: sour cream pie
review: We love this pie. I made it for Thanksgiving but used Sun Maid Fruit Bits instead of the Craisins and it disappeared before I could take a photo. Rich and creamy and smooth with the fruit cutting some of the richness.

name: herbamare substitute
review: I should have reviewed this several years ago! I've been making this recipe (sans kelp) and I love it on anything. Potatoes, yams, other veggies, meat etc. I finally realized that kelp is just seaweed, so I'm going to be adding it this time.

name: five grain hot cereal
review: I ground everything in my Whisper Mill, so that wasn't a problem. I used 1 T sucanat to cook it for 2 1/2 minutes on the stove. I always burn the pot though! Came out very creamy and just the right amount of sweetness. Didn't need extra sugar or milk. Kind of like Malt 'O Meal. You could drizzle some maple syrup over the top too. Definitely a keeper! Thanks Sharon. UPDATE: I am now gluten free and watching grains. So I tried using 1/2 C amaranth seeds, 1/2 C white rice (lower arsenic), 1/2 C almond flour and then used the oatmeal and cornmeal. Turns out just as easy and good. But I have problems burning the bottom of the pot with these recipes! So I am going to try to make it in my Instant Pot next time.

name: baklava salmon  salmon with honey  butter  walnuts  and mustard
review: When I was looking at this recipe my husband said "Nuts on fish? Can you just leave them off?" So I put them in the blender until they were close to the same consistency as the bread crumbs. He didn't realize they were on there until I told him. We all enjoyed it this way.

name: chilies rellenos casserole
review: As written, the recipe is not at all spicy and was a bit doughy for my taste. I made a second batch (half the recipe), using 7 oz of green chiles and 1/3 cup flour. I'd reduce the flour further. I sauteed about 5 oz fresh chorizo sausage with the onions and layered this on top of the chiles. Like another reviewer, I toasted my tortillas, but I just throw them on a gas burner and let them sit there for a few seconds. This version was a 4 star for me. I thought the filling was more stodgy than quiche-like, and will reduce flour further

name: shrimp and butternut squash in coconut milk broth
review: I left the shrimp whole, as my daughter isn't always a fan. I thought it would be easier for her to pick out. I had to use white rice and dried cilantro because that is what I had on hand. Otherwise, I followed the recipe.

name: pumpkin pie dip
review: I made this to take to a pot luck lunch at work. It's the first time I've come home with a container that's almost as full as it was when I brought it. I served it with green and red apple slices, graham crackers and fresh pineapple. I have to admit, I really didn't care for it when I tried it myself, and I typically like most things pumpkin. My daughter thought it was okay though.

name: fabulous ham bone and lentil soup
review: I made a few slight alterations to use up what we hand on hand. I used two ham bones that my mother in law sent home from Thanksgiving to make the broth. I also used crushed tomatoes instead of regular canned tomatoes cut up and dried parsley instead of fresh. I didn't have any, but my family really enjoyed it. Served with a loaf of fresh bread. A very comforting meal on a cold day.

name: black eyed peas salad
review: This was not only delicious, but very pretty. I omitted the olives and the carrots, because I had none. Also had to use apple cider vinegar, because I could not get the balsamic open (darn arthritis). I tasted the dressing and added no sugar, the honey was enough for me. A good way to use the last zucchini and salsa peppers from my garden.

name: the cheesecake factory pumpkin cheesecake by todd wilbur
review: I made this to take to a Christmas party this weekend. I had roasted a fresh pumpkin and made pumpkin puree to use instead of canned. I was uncertain of baking a cheesecake without a water bath, but it turned out great! Done perfectly at 60 minutes with no cracking at all!

name: black eyed peas salad
review: This is a wonderful bean salad. I used tinned beans and made half a batch. My big/only change was to eliminate the sugar. The honey was more than enough sweetening.

name: buttered wine rice
review: FYI 90g of butter is apx. 4 1/2 Tablespoons. I used instant white rice because that is what I had on hand. Followed directions exactly and it turned out great. If I do it this way again I may add more rice as I had a lot of liquid still in the pan.

name: crock pot chicken in wine
review: This got mixed reviews at our house. DD didn't care for it, DH thought it was good and I only liked the mushrooms. The sauce was much thinner than we would have liked. Next time I may thicken it up after cooking or reduce the amount of wine/broth before cooking. We served it over rice. I did use some of the liquid from the chicken and added it to the rice the when cooking to add flavor.

name: tasty tandoori  sweet potatoes
review: My market did not carry the paste, but I was able to make one from a spice mix they had. It was very spicy, so I did not add pepper flakes. After 20 minutes, I added a diced red bell pepper that was hanging around. It all worked together beautifully. I might try adding a little brown sugar next time, as I do like a spicy-sweet combo, too. Made for the cook-a-thon in honor of Susie D.

name: the world s best cookies
review: Great flavor, texture. Will certainly make again. Thanks for sharing.

name: spicy baked cod
review: SO easy to make a dinner for one. Only needed 90 seconds in my microwave. I also added a squirt of fresh lemon juice.

name: apple butter spice cookies
review: I am very happy with these cookies. They are exactly "light and tasty" as advertised. I used my homemade apple butter, and it worked out fine. Next time I'm planning on increasing the amounts of raisins and nuts (I used walnuts), but this is not to say the ones I made today are not good just as they are. Thank you for the recipe.

name: moroccan style spicy pickled vegetables
review: This is a great, quick pickle recipe that can use all sorts of vegetables. I made it using carrots, bell pepper, onion, cauliflower, olives and garlic. Only skipped the tomato, which I thought might just turn to mush. The marinade has a great balance of flavours and was ready in no time.

name: doctored up scrambled eggs
review: We really enjoyed these delicious, flavorful eggs. I added a few extra tablespoons of milk to extend the recipe to feed a few more people. Also, I chopped up a couple of mushrooms and cooked them with the ham before adding the egg mixture. These eggs were a big hit with my guests. Thank you for sharing this wonderful recipe. **Made for 2017 Football Pool**

name: baked fettuccine
review: This was super easy and tasted great. I used different noodles and used half heavy cream and half milk since I had no half and half. I made this for the vegetarians in the family for Christmas. It was enjoyed by all and I'll be using it in the future for regular meals and side dishes. Thanks for posting!

name: colorful corn   veggie casserole
review: This was a hearty recipe that my whole family enjoyed. We do enjoy our vegetarian/dairy dishes, and this was no exception. It was also very creamy, which is simething I enjoy very much!

name: posole  mexican soup with pork and hominy
review: This is DELICIOUS! I used leftover roast pork shoulder that just fell apart in the soup, but it was still amazing. Love the flavors.

name: pork mixed bean chili
review: This recipe was a HUGE hit with our family. Even my picky eater loved it. The adults mixed tapatio sauce into their bowls to spice it up. The kids mixed cheddar and sour cream into their bowls.

name: baked seasoned salmon
review: We really enjoyed this dish. Unfortunately, with all the butter, my healthy salmon wasn't so healthy. That's probably why it was so good! Next time I may try to cut back on the butter and see how it turns out! Update - The one good thing about all that butter, I used the extra to saute some fresh shrimp and zucchini noodles. It was just as delicious as the salmon!

name: snowman bouquet or pops
review: So very darling, great special treat for the kids

name: whole 30 hibachi chicken
review: Simple, flavorful, and nice and juicy!

name: tomato and barley soup
review: Good easy soup. Just needed some salt added. I also topped with fresh parsley.

name: south america quinoa
review: This was good but WAY too much oil. I'll use 1/4 cup next time. I also added more lemon juice and salt and pepper.

name: parmesan salmon
review: We couldn't decide between three or four stars for this one. If you are looking for a good salmon this is a recipe for you. If you want an amazing salmon recipe, this might not satisfy your need. However, it was extremely easy to put together and cooks quickly, so it makes a good week night meal.

name: pork chops   apple butter
review: I made this using 4 boneless chops. I did opt to use the garlic and onion powder on the chops. I put a cup of unsweetened applesauce in the pan, laying the chops on top and then spooning homemade apple butter on top. I forgot to oil the pan, but didn't have any problem with sticking, so I will continue to leave it out in the future. Plenty of liquid was created during cooking, so I am happy I didn't add any water like the recipe called for. So easy to prep!

name: emeril s burger seasoning
review: Thanks so much for this fab recipe. I tried it out on my husband he loved it. It was spicy, but not too spicy for him.

name: pumpkin gooey butter cake   paula deen
review: Baked in a round springform pan and topped it pecans and caramel when serving.

name: almond cupcakes
review: Hi, the recipe was fabulous. I used jumbo muffin cups and the recipe was really easy to follow. I had a problem with getting the cupcakes out of the pan, even when using plenty of nonstick cooking spray. One of them didn't make it, but that's the one I used to try it out. I tried the recipe again and used shortening as well and they all came out but it took some effort. I don't think it's the fault of the recipe; just a warning in case anyone faces the same issue. Next time I will use shortening to grease the cups.

name: low carb pumpkin sausage soup
review: While we thought this was good, we also thought it was a little on the thin and bland side. I would recommend using a spicy sausage and probably would leave the water out. We added a few extra mushrooms and onions. We also added more garlic, seasoning and added some fresh ground pepper.

name: super fast chicken pot pie
review: Another winner of a dinner here. Simple and flavorful. I used leftover roasted chicken that I had made the night before and then used the red pepper alternative as listed. Hubby does not like green beans in his pies so I just used a mix of frozen white corn, petite peas and fresh carrots which I sliced thin and micro-cooked for a bit to soften before adding to the dish. Susie you will be missed and I'll always think of you and your kindness when I make this dish again and again.

name: jumbo shrimp parmesan
review: For sure one of the best shrimps recipes! The preparation was super easy and the result superb! We enjoyed this over spaghetti!

name: traditional english cheddar cauliflower cheese   gratin
review: This was good. We weren't crazy about the breadcrumbs on top. Next time I may try panko or leave the breadcrumbs out all together.

name: chicken with balsamic fig sauce
review: That's a superlative recipe! We enjoyed this as Sunday lunch with could not be better. I simply sliced the onions and quartered the figs and wow! what for great result, you made my family very happy with this completely new recipe! This recipe will be a keeper for sure!

name: cauliflower with tangy mustard sauce
review: We didn't care for the texture of the cauliflower in this. Microwaving turned it to mush. Next time I may try roasting it in the oven.

name: grandma s big boy strawberry pie
review: This is a long-time favorite of mine. I grew up with Bob's Big Boy restaurant and this is the strawberry pie that they served. I loved how the pie slice stayed together when I cut it and slid it on to the plate. To clarify, the recipe should state 'one baked pie crust'.

name: rich chocolate cupcakes
review: Awesome recipe; easy to put together and baking time for me (with jumbo muffin cups) was 20 minutes. I didn't use liners, and used soy milk for the regular milk; that was my only substitution. Even with greasing with shortening, especially the bottoms, I had a few cupcakes that still stuck to the bottom of the cups. These pans are quite old so I ordered new ones today; thinking the nonstick coating may be worn out. Any advice? I've Googled for tips and techniques and feel I've tried all of them. I also made red velvet cupcakes in these same pans, which use buttermilk, and had no sticking. Does that make a difference, I wonder?

name: seared salmon with balsamic glaze
review: Next time, I may reduce the amount of water. Otherwise, I'd keep everything the same. Served with French green beans and rices vegetable pilaf.

name: eggplant  aubergine  croutons
review: Thanks a lot to suggesting us to "precook and remove water" from the eggplants in the oven with salt prior frying them. This saves a lot of time and the eggplants soak less oil. Great recipe!

name: marvelous broccoli salad
review: This is even better the next day. I chopped the onion instead of leaving it in rings. Next time I may add sunflower seeds and raisins or dried cranberries.

name: pizza spirals
review: We have both meat eaters and a vegetarian in our home. So we simply left the pepperoni off. Didn't spiral very easily. But, they were very tasty.

name: jo mama s world famous spaghetti
review: This recipe REALLY doesn't need any more positive reviews lol. I made this with hot Italian chicken sausage, ground. I also halved the recipe (it was very easy to cut in half!). I used about 3/4 cup of water even though I did simmer for about an hour. Oh, and I used Italian diced tomatoes! It was very easy, very satisfying and a wonderful meal; thank you!!

name: skinnybaker s healthy chocolate cupcakes
review: Sorry this didn't work out for me! Flavor wasn't very good

name: pumpkin and black bean soup
review: I made this using homemade puréed pumpkin. I liked it but the rest of the family didn't. Taking the leftovers to work tomorrow to share. We'll see what the ladies think.

name: the realtor s red velvet brownies with white chocolate icing
review: Hi, I made these for a neighbor and she said they were yummy. I tried a little sliver of it myself and thought the same. I didn't make the icing, because they were already plenty sweet, but it would be wonderful with frosting for sure. I made an error by adding a little baking powder as a leavening agent, but that seemed to form "cracks" instead. Mine didn't turn out as "fluffy looking" as the pics indicated. But I didn't follow the instructions to a "T' (didn't make the paste) so I'll be sure to be more careful next time. These really would be wonderful for a holiday or special occasion!

name: lemon garlic salmon
review: I doubled the garlic for this recipe. But that is the norm for us. Next time I may add even more cause we love our garlic. This made for a quick, yet tasty, week night meal. Served with a side of asparagus.

name: balsamic asparagus
review: Was in need of a quick, yet tasty, way to cook some asparagus. This recipe was both of those. Served as a side to salmon.

name: homemade cheeseburger macaroni hamburger helper
review: Hi, I made this for a neighbor and her family so this is their review on it! I followed the recipe except that I used chicken broth for the water, and added some black pepper to the sauce mix. It was very easy to make and came together easily. No problem with the cooking process. When I tasted the pasta to make sure it was done, I thought it tasted pretty good. But the family I made it for said it was bland, and they didn't enjoy it. I might try to this again and double up the seasonings to see if that helps? Not sure yet. I'm trying to find casseroles/recipes that are family friendly and fairly guaranteed to be enjoyed. Thanks for sharing this and I wish it had worked out for me!

name: hamburger noodle bake
review: Hi, I made this for a neighbor and she really enjoyed it. I took advice from other reviewers and used spaghetti sauce for the tomato sauce (added additional seasonings to taste). I used whole wheat elbow macaroni and mozzarella cheese. I baked it, covered for 20 minutes. Layering was a bit difficult (the sour cream mix was hard to spread) so I sort of "dotted" the mixture over the noodles. Thanks for sharing a great recipe!

name: light chocolate mousse
review: Amazing, light dessert that everyone raved about. I used it as a compliment to Ice Wine Cabernet Franc. It went beautifully with this ruby port type dessert wine. This is going into the "make again" file. Rich and chocolatey without the guilt. Thanks!

name: banana bread brownies
review: I made this for a neighbor and she really enjoyed it. I used about 4 small ripe bananas and baked for 30 minutes in a 13X9 pan. I threw it in the freezer for about an hour but it was still very moist so it really is more of a cake than a brownie. But still delicious. My neighbor said it was sweet enough w/o the frosting (I made a cream cheese frosting for her at the last minute)

name: marie s tender sirloin tip roast
review: Perfect. Simple and to the point instructions.

name: easy moist banana blueberry muffins
review: These look and smell wonderful. I used four small overripe bananas but I wonder if that was too many. Batter was a bit more runny that I would like! I made jumbo muffins and baked for 25 minutes. I thought I had over baked (they were quite brown) but I actually think they turned out fine. I might decrease the time just a bit next time, though, to see what happens.

name: nestle toll house chocolate chip pan cookie
review: Made as directed and used a 13X9 pan. Baked for 25 minutes. I noticed another reviewer used 3/4 cup butter and I might try that next time! Not sure if my baking time was too high (others baked for much less it seems) but they seemed just fine!

name: sauteed shrimp parmesan
review: Quick and easy to make. We doubled the amount of garlic and may even add a little more next time.

name: crispy cheese cauliflower
review: Made this tonight as a side to some grilled chicken. I had to use shredded Parmesan because that's what I had on hand. Next time I will use the grated.

name: white chili   football soup
review: I noticed the review on making this vegetarian. I had been thinking of making another recipe, but made this instead. I cooked dry beans instead of using canned. From experience I know the mild chiles don't do much for me, so I added a chopped jalapeno to the onions to saute. Used a bit more cayenne. I also added chopped cilantro and a sliced green onion to the garnishes. It was very tasty. Half the recipe made four large soup bowl servings for us.

name: tsr version of red lobster cheddar bay biscuits by todd wilbur
review: I cut the recipe in half and made 4 good sized biscuits. I did have to add just an additional slash of milk to get the dough to stay together. Next time I may make more of the butter mixture to go on top. Overall they were a very good addition to our meal.

name: fresh basil tortellini salad
review: Made this as a side dish to go with some grilled salad. We weren't crazy about the carrots, but enjoyed everything else about it. May take another reviewer's suggestion and substitute grape tomatoes for the carrots next time. I took the leftovers for lunch the next day. I just had to freshen it up a little, but it was still delicious.

name: lemon buttercream
review: Loved the creamy texture and the wonderful lemon flavor, until I added the zest. I wasn't a fan of what the zest did to the wonderfully creamy texture. So, I made another batch and left the zest out. Unfortunately, it wouldn't hold it's shape firmly when piping. I added more powdered sugar. But, by the time it was stiff enough, it didn't taste as lemony. I didn't want to add more lemon juice because then I would be at a softer consistency again. So I added lemon extract until it was closer to the flavor I was looking for. This recipe was a great starting point for me, I just needed to tweak it a little to fit my needs.

name: microwave snow peas
review: What a quick and easy way to make snow peas. Great when you don't have a lot of time, which is often for this busy family. Will make these again!

name: rice krispie easter treats
review: Easy and cute. I had to use double the amount of chocolate for it to stay together.

name: elbows and ham bake
review: Baked it longer to get it really crunchy on top. YUM!

name: awesome baked pork chops
review: Delicious! I used an organic all natural cream of mushroom soup which is a little thinner, but still wonderful. Just needed a bit more salt with using that.

name: chicken breast grand marnier
review: I made this for dinner tonight. My families comments in a nut shell were that the chicken was cooked well, but they weren't crazy about the sauce. Bummer, cause I doubled the sauce based on the other review so there would be plenty to go around.

name: balsamic roasted asparagus
review: I sampled the asparagus when I took it out of the oven and it was good. However, I didn't care for it as much with the sauce. The rest of my family felt the same.

name: cheesy ham penne casserole
review: I didn't realize we were out of penne so used bowtie pasta. Really yummy!

name: tomato avocado salad
review: Needed lunch fast, but it had to be vegetarian and gluten free to suit the family members eating it. We thought it was good, but a little bland. Added a little extra garlic, salt and pepper and that seemed to solve the problem. I didn't have fresh cilantro or lime on hand or I may have tried that like another reviewer suggested. Sounds delish!

name: roasted asparagus with feta
review: I forgot to put the feta on before putting it in the oven. So I sprinkled it on and popped it back in the oven for a couple of minutes. Still turned out fine. Made as a side of sautéed shrimp.

name: banana yogurt muffins
review: Made these for the hubby. I used non. fat vanilla Greek yogurt and buttermilk. One banana was smashed and one chopped. He gave them four stars.

name: kittencal s white cake
review: Wow, nearly 9 years later and I pulled this recipe out of my collection to make for my Mom's 91st birthday. I'm so glad I did. I made both the cake layers (two 8" cake layers) and the frosting the week before I was going to serve them and I froze both cake layers and frosting. The night before I was going to serve the cake, I put the cake layers and frosting in the refrigerator to thaw. The next morning the cake layers were nice and moist. The frosting just needed to be stirred up with a spoon to get it back to a smooth consistency. Rave reviews from everyone. I recommend you save this recipe to your recipe collection, also. original review written on 9/6/2009 This was served to rave reviews at a birthday party today. I followed the instructions exactly, including using Duncan Hines Moist Deluxe Classic White. I baked it in two 8" round cake pans. On Kittencal's suggestion, I paired it with recipe #90142. It was perfect. I was proud to serve this cake and will make it again.

name: no bake rice krispies peanut butter granola bars  lower fat
review: As I have now made these about 15 times I figured it is time I made a review LOL! I am giving 5 stars because the beauty of this recipe is its versatility--I have used cashew butter, chocolate chips, and dried cherries together, almond butter with chocolate chips and mint extract, and peanut butter with chocolate chips and crushed pretzels. I always use old fashioned oats pulsed in my coffee grinder a bit, and I often use a mixture of rice crispy cereal and plain cheerios (those cereals that languish in the pantry toward the end of the box LOL). You can totally make these in the microwave; I mix the nut butter, honey, and about 1/4 sugar and microwave for about 45 seconds, stir, then pop it back in the microwave for about 20 seconds. Easy peasy and dangerously quick! The only major tweak I make every time is one I highly recommend--if you use natural nut butters, add about 1/2 teaspoon of salt with the dry ingredients. It will make these taste much more like their store bought counterparts. My kids and I inhale these almost as fast as I can make them, so thank you for the recipe!

name: egyptian macaroni bechamel
review: I made this dish for my Egyptian husband. He thought it was delicious & very authentic. He said the only thing is that Egyptians would use Mozzarella not Parmesan in the dish. Parmesan is not a cheese that they can get easily.

name: spaghetti with clam sauce
review: Usually I have to sell a recipe to DH, but tonight, I was the hesitant one about Clam Sauce! DH is used to some Italian-Americans making it for a sporting club. I have avoided recipes for spaghetti that don't involve cans of tomato product. DH had critiques requesting bigger pieces of clam so he could taste the clam easily so I would try whole baby clams next time. I was not sure at all I would like this dish, plain and simple. But I did enjoy it very much, despite my prejudices. I was surprised that the recipe did indeed need an entire bunch of parsley. I splurged on DeCecco spaghetti noodles, the best noodles at my local market, and I was glad I did. I made the recipe with 10 oz. of spaghetti noodles, although there were only 2 of us. I must have been beguiled, because we ate all of the recipe during one dinner! So you converted me, Maito! Thank you for sharing this recipe! Made "For Your Consideration".

name: bobotie
review: This was a nice change of pace for us - reminded us of sausage (I used the fennel) without the unhealthy attributes of sausage. I used a mellow Madras curry powder, and it did not overwhelm us. We loved the accent of apples. After a lunch for 3 adults (with 2 hearty appetites), we had about half left over. We plan to reheat that for breakfast with fried eggs on the side. I took off one star only because there was a lot of liquid, making it difficult to get clean slices. I wonder how this would turn out if I used a meatloaf pan with an insert to drain off the excess liquid (I would probably halve the recipe). Sorry I forgot about the bay leaf garnish before I put it in the oven.

name: pumpkin ginger pancakes with ginger butter
review: Wonderful! DH was worried that the ginger would overwhelm him; then he complained that he could hardly taste the ginger in the candied ginger butter! LOL, I had my pancakes just as the recipe presented, and I enjoyed the subtle ginger taste. Looking forward to making these again, and I will always remember Susie D fondly!

name: no guilt soup
review: Very good! It can't get much simpler than this! I will keep this in mind for cooking away from home; but at home, I'd rather steam fresh carrots and green beans, and probably cook up my own beans, too. It makes up about 9 cups of hearty soup.

name: bordelaise sauce with mushrooms
review: W.O.W.!!!! We are still talking about our dinner last night - we ate at the best place in town: home! I served this sauce with prime sirloin cap steaks cooked at 132F for 5 hours, sous vide - it was so nice and tender. But this sauce, what a sauce! I had made a simpler version of Bordelaise sauce before, but this version was sublime! I was thankful that I cooked the steaks sous vide and that they could hang in the 132F bath so I could give full attention to making this sauce. With all the sauteing and simmering, this sauces takes a bit of time. I completed the sauce, then seared my steaks for an easy but scrumptious meal.

name: chicken fettuccine  cajun style
review: What a Manly Meal! Perfect for Bar Food, people will order more and more beer to calm the seasonings! I went in a different direction than most reviewers: I used ALL of the butter called for, and it ALL ended up in the sauce. Cajuns like their butter! In the Sauce, I changed to: 4 minced garlic cloves, 1/2 tsp cayenne pepper, 1/4 tsp white pepper, 1/4 tsp black pepper, 1/4 tsp Tabasco, and a rounded 1/2 cup of chopped green onion. In the Chicken Seasoning, I changed to: 1/4 tsp white pepper, 1 tsp garlic powder, 1/4 cayenne pepper, 1/8 tsp black pepper, rounded 1/4 tsp cumin. My sauce reduced to a dense chili-like sauce after 1 hour of simmering. Using 1/2 cup of butter to cook the chicken cubes ensured that the chicken cubes were submerged in the hot liquid, and therefore cooked more evenly. I call this a "Manly Meal" because the flavoring is intense, but, oddly, the amounts of spices I used didn't quite reach 2-alarm hotness that a measly 0.01 ounce Thai Chili Pepper produced the night before. Because the spices are so intense and so likely to stain whatever container, I would not recommend doubling the sauce and freezing for another day. Cajun cooking requires time to seal in layers of seasoning - so why not make it a quasi-religious experience the day you plan to eat it? By the way, we gobbled this up, and experienced no digestive complaints. We will make this again (just not right before having labs drawn or a doctor's appointment)! By the way, we topped ours with freshly grated Parmesano Reggioano, because it's special, like us.

name: double chocolate muffins
review: Recipe turned out wonderful. I too used 1/2 cup sugar based on reviews and used mini chocolate chips!

name: cocoa powder cookies
review: Recipe turned out wonderful. Thank you!

name: chicken with apricot ginger sauce
review: The "no-name" chicken breasts from our local market were still typical U.S.-oversized chicken breasts; I wish I had thought to slice each breast in half horizontally prior to cooking. It's hard in the U.S. to find a "normal" chicken breast. Although the breasts were well seared in the given cooking time (I guessed at medium-high heat, no heat level was specified), they were way under-cooked. I added about 4 minutes per side. During this time, I wished I had chosen to cook the breasts sous vide instead - that way I would be certain that the breasts had reached the proper temperature throughout, then I could have seared them just before serving (and I wouldn't have to clean the stove area from grease splatters). As for the apricot-ginger sauce, it should be halved even for 4 over-sized chicken breasts. The sauce was pleasant, but not addictive.

name: baked homemade granola  lower fat
review: This flavor in this granola was OK. Mine didn't cook up nice and crisp ...so I don't know if it was because it wasn't cooked long enough or because of the water/maple syrup combination. I will finish this off, but move onto another recipe!

name: baked balsamic chicken
review: I've recently discovered the deliciousness of balsamic vinegar and so I was excited to try this recipe. I used the ingredients as stated and used boneless, skinless chicken breasts. I started them out at 350 degrees for 11 minutes and then realized the recipe stated that the temperature should be at 400 degrees. So I bumped up the temperature. I kept an eye on them to make sure that I pulled them out as soon as they were done. Even with that, they came out dry and very unflavorful. I think the only way to save these is to cover them up with barbeque sauce. This recipe is not for me.

name: roasted zucchini with thyme
review: Recipe didn't specify if the thyme was fresh or dried. I used fresh and it really isn't have much flavor. I assume that means I should have used dried. I'll try it again sometime using dried and update my review then.

name: just chicken livers
review: Very tasty, although Lucy wanted to post the review and photo...

name: turkey noodle soup
review: I made this two ways. The first time I made it following the directions to a t. DH gave it four stars. The second time I made it while a gluten intolerant family was eating with us. I added rice instead of noodles and left the butter/flour mixture out. They gave it three stars.

name: garlic thyme chicken
review: We doubled the garlic, which is the norm for our garlic loving family. I wouldn't hesitate to add even more, as the thyme is the predominant flavor in this recipe and we'd like a little more of the garlic flavor to show through. Over all, it was easy to make and DH enjoyed it. We didn't have any rice on hand but I am sure it would be delicious with the juices from this chicken on top.

name: neelys  braised mustard greens with bacon and raisins
review: Didn't have any raisins, so I left them out. Other than that, I followed the recipe. My family isn't a huge fan of greens. But they ate them like this. Bacon and garlic are a must with my crew.

name: black bean   corn tacos with radish salsa   feta
review: We are not typically fans of radishes. But there was a bag of them in our farm share and I didn't want to waste them. My can of corn was bigger than called for, but I threw the whole thing in anyway and I always double my garlic in recipes. I used a jalapeño pepper, and my feta was reduced fat, but it turned out fabulous. I'll admit, we weren't expecting to like these and instead we all went back for seconds! It's not often our entire family agrees on something, so a five star rating from this crew is a true complement!

name: creamy asparagus soup
review: This is really a great asparagus soup; I followed everything except the thyme; we don't care for it; but that parmesan at the end bring it up a few notches; thanks or posting.

name: chile verde  chicken or pork
review: OMG, Fabulous! I wanted to lick my bowl to get every last drop. This was my first time cooking with tomatillos, and I panicked when I could not find canned ones, but I bought 24 oz. of fresh tomatillos, removed the husks, washed, and cut in quarters -- I am no longer afraid. On a hunch I used 8 oz. of diced Hatch chilies and 7 oz. diced green chilies, which resulted in perfect heat for our 2-alarm threshold. We used chicken this round, but I hear it's even better with pork shoulder. I cooked for 15 minutes at pressure in a 6-qt. electric pressure cooker, but I'll use my 8-qt. next time to better handle the volume. This is a KEEPER!

name: collard greens   it s good for you
review: I had a bag of fresh collards from the fam share to use. My family isn't crazy about them normally, but they seemed to like these. Doubled the garlic. Didn't measure the collards. I just used what I had. Left out the optional brown sugar and reduced the red pepper flakes by half. DD said she would have liked them more if I also reduced the amount of black pepper. It's all about taking a good basic recipe and adjusting it to what your family prefers. Thanks for this recipe that got them to eat their greens.

name: huevos rancheros tacos
review: Tasty and easy. My oven is out, so I threw the tortillas on the gas burner to toast one side, then flipped onto a comal and topped with the other ingredients. I used a poached egg, because I could do that in the egg cooker. I'm going to try this with refried beans, too.

name: skillet chicken  stuffing and gravy
review: We have a family memeber that is gluten intolerant so I used Aldi's liveGfree brand of gluten free chicken stuffing and a 12 oz. package of Campbell's Oven Sauces Creamy Garlic Butter Chicken for the gravy. It smelled so good and the family really enjoyed it.

name: asian mole
review: A lot of chocolate, but not too sweet. Very interesting. I was going to serve over chicken, but I think green beans are best for me. My prep time was long (we had some business that extended into my normal cooking time), so I prepared the sauce tonight to serve tomorrow. I was surprised that I had black sesame seeds on hand, so I ended up making as written. I'll update on how well it reheats.

name: vij s yogurt and tamarind marinated grilled chicken
review: This recipe was AMAZING! Perfectly flavorful, not spicy so kids loved it too. I ordered tamarind paste from Amazon.

name: hawaiian pulled pork sandwiches
review: Really tasty recipe. I couldn't find the teriyaki spice so I just used a teriyaki marinade. I also used just a couple tablespoons of sriracha in place of the chili sauce. Served with some Hawaiian macaroni salad!

name: cod with spiced red lentils
review: Tasty recipe. I didn't want my lentils mushy so cooked them according to the package time instead of the recipe instructions.

name: mojo beef kabobs
review: These were FANTASTIC! Great flavor, tender meat. Really good.

name: avocado pizza
review: This was delicious! I used mini naan for the crust. Only 4 stars because the cooking time or temperature was off. I wonder if it's supposed to be 180C instead of F (which would be 350F). At the end of 20 minutes the cheese still wasn't melted. So I turned the heat up to 350F for 5 minutes to finish it off.

name: indian kadai chicken
review: Good recipe. The spiciness was just right for us, especially over rice.

name: rotisserie vinaigrette chicken salad
review: Great dressing! It makes a lot more than you need for the salad. Next time I'll swap the celery for something else, maybe shredded carrots.

name: easy cube steak
review: AMAZING! I used my favorite Chef's Seasoning mix and skipped the onions in the skillet. Also used a grill pan since it was handy. Once the steaks were done I mixed a tablespoon of flour into the pan drippings and added 3/4 cup of beef stock. Brought it to a boil to make a simple gravy.

name: brussels  sprouts with garlic and lemon
review: So simple, yet so good! We're fans of steamed Brussels sprouts, yet these could lure in those on the fence with their quasi-roasted allure.

name: mango popsicles  durofrios de mango
review: Not giving a star review since I tweaked it so much. I swapped a small can of pineapple juice for the water and skipped the sugar. I also skipped the ice since our mango was frozen. SO delicious!

name: hawaiian salad
review: Delicious!

name: orange and mango breakfast smoothie
review: This was a great addition to our Hawaiian dinner! This smoothie's not just for breakfast. I used frozen mango and fresh orange juice and it was just yum! Thanks Mami J!

name: maui gold pineapple salsa
review: Vibrant colors - a beautiful tropical salsa or condiment.

name: chicken lime mojo
review: Wonderful earthy taste! I baked this the night before (350F/50 minutes), and reheated 45 minutes at 250F, and served it with fried rice.

name: broiled mahi mahi with parsleyed tomatoes and feta
review: This was a very tasty dish. I really enjoyed the onion tomato mixture with the fish. The feta and lemon are a must so don't skip them.

name: hawaiian slaw
review: Quick and easy to make this was a nice change from our regular slaw. I enjoyed the macadamia nuts but toasted almonds would work and would be a little easier on the budget. Made for Susie's WORLD TOUR 2018 , HAWAII by one of the Pantry Pirates

name: linguine with marinara sauce and meatballs
review: We loved this quick, easy and flavorful dish. The sauce and meatballs were very yummy. I added a few sprinkles of sugar to reduce the tartness of the tomato, and I mixed the sauce into the pasta instead of spooning it on top. Served topped with Parmesan cheese and fresh basil, this was a dinner favorite. It was even better the next day. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018 - Malta**

name: widow s soup
review: This is a fast weeknight meal that will help clean out your refrigerator! I used kohlrabi "noodles" which worked great. I loved the creaminess of the melted cheese in it (I used vegan chive cream cheese).

name: good  n easy macaroni salad
review: This was a great salad for a warm summer day. I made it for dinner for myself one day and lunch for two the next . It was cool and hearty at the same time. After trying it as written I added some yellow and red pepper and some cherry tomatoes. Delish! Made for Suzie's World Tour

name: creamy   easy broccoli slaw
review: What as easy way to make coleslaw, Love it but only used 1 tsp Splenda; I also added some of my fresh tarragon,

name: glazed carrots in the microwave
review: Quick, easy, tasty - my kind of side dish! I've never used orange zest in my glazed carrots and I think I would add more next time because I couldn't really taste it. I cooked the carrots for a total of 3-4 minutes and it was just right. Thanks Miami J!

name: miso broiled scallops
review: Made as written, I marinated the scallops for about 45 minutes and found despite all the delicious flavors in the marinade they didn't really take hold. The onion was probably the most dominant. So while the scallops were good, it didn't seem quite worth the effort. Made for Culinary Quest 2016 testing updating review

name: two way barbecued steak  churrasco
review: I made this as listed and surprisingly, I preferred the pineapple aioli, which I thought sounded like a strange combination of flavours. I have to say though - we really stink of garlic now! I would make this again, maybe with just the yummy pineapple aioli. Thanks Life Is Good!

name: german home fried potatoes
review: Outstanding potatoes! I cooked them in the microwave to save time and not heat up the kitchen. Starting with the cooked potatoes they broke down more then when starting with raw but they were faster, cooked more evenly and tasted fully cooked. I love onions and potatoes together and the garlic was a nice touch though I wasn't sure when I was supposed to add it , so I let them cook a little then added it in. Made for Susie's World Tour by one of the Pantry Pirates

name: argentinian tropical tincho
review: This was good but more like a wine cooler than a cocktail, and a little thin. After trying it I added more of the pineapple vodka. (I infused my own vodka and it was delicious). The wine I used was also slightly effervescent and shaking it knocked a lot of that out, and the lid kept trying to pop off the cocktail shaker. I left out the club soda since I knew the bubble would go flat with shaking. I think muddling the mint and adding the vodka in the glass then topping and lightly stirring with the wine would be improve sparkle.

name: krafne  croatian doughnuts
review: More of a dense donut than what I'm used to, but still good!

name: ground beef stuffed green bell peppers ii   oven or crock pot
review: Made the oven version in my shallow dutch oven instead of a casserole. Made as written and absolutely delicious!

name: creamy macaroni chicken soup  sopas
review: I wasn't sure about this recipe but it really surprised me. Absolutely delicious! I topped it with a bit of chopped parsley.

name: old kentucky favorite potato salad
review: I was surprised that my family gave this four stars, as they usually aren't a fan of potato salads without mustard in them. They did request that I use less chopped celery next time, but otherwise had no objections to me straying from our usual potato salad recipe. I will make this again whenever we are wanting something a little different. Served as a side to grilled chicken and veggie skewers.

name: country hamburger lentil soup   crock pot
review: Good and really easy. Made as written, just topped with a sprig of fresh basil.

name: mango sherbet  helado de mango
review: This was a little bit icier than I hoped for. If I make again I will add a tiny bit of guar gum to help control that. The flavor was really nice though. Made for Susie’s World Tour

name: champinones al ajillo  garlic fried mushrooms
review: Healthy, tasty and ready in just a few minutes!

name: sausage breakfast muffins  oamc
review: I tried adding some spices like sage, chili powder, garlic powder, and a little salt but still felt they were pretty bland. Maybe needed a lot more salt.

name: pickle sauce  michael smith
review: Fresh and flavorful! I had jarred dill spears, not pickles, so used six which seemed to be the right amount. If you want a thicker sauce like tartar you could use less lemon juice or dry the pickles.

name: lemon cilantro rice pilaf
review: Turn your plain white rice into something festive! This recipe makes a small amount so you may want to double or triple it for leftovers.

name: pan grilled pork chops
review: These were excellent. I cooked them to 142F, deglazing the pan with white wine and fortifying the pan reduction with butter. Served with roasted carrots and Amish cabbage with bacon. Made for Susie's World Tour.

name: chile and spice rubbed pork tenderloin with honey lime glaze
review: Wow, Super delicious! We loved the herb and spice combination with the pork. I reduced the chipotle and red pepper quite a bit but it still had a good amount of heat which balanced well with the lime honey glaze. I guessed how much of that I would use and wished I had made a little more. I used pork steaks instead of pork loin and cooked them on the grill, yum, yum, yum! We will definitely make this again.

name: copycat  green giant niblets corn in butter sauce
review: Made this as a side for dinner tonight. I reduced the salt, as we have a family member on a low sodium diet. Also sweetened with stevia. I served it with chicken and stuffing. Everyone enjoyed it.

name: easy gaucho beans
review: We expected to love these Gaucho beans. Somehow the carrots and tomatoes overwhelmed the 2 cans of kidney beans, and we missed the magical bean starch. For our taste preference, I would scale back on the carrots and tomatoes to a supporting role instead of a starring role. I think this dish would be a great way to get kids to eat veggies.

name: bean salad pizzazz
review: Like my Grandma's bean salad with added pizzazz of jalapeno and citrus! Because it doesn't get soggy, this is a perfect salad for packing for lunch at work or a potluck. A good item to put together in meal prep on the weekend and have on hand for side dishes throughout the week.

name: argentinian steak sandwiches
review: I just happened to have a perfectly ripe avocado, some tomatoes from the garden, and some warm fresh baguette in the house at the same time, AND I was thinking about lunch, so here we are! I seasoned my steak with Goya Adobo seasoning and a bit of applewood smoked salt and cooked them on my grill pan. I did add some more salt to the Chimichurri, too (personal preference). The end product is a tasty sandwich that is pretty as well, something that you would see on the menu at a nice cafe. Thanks for posting, PanNan! Made for SWT2018 Argentina by a fellow member of Team Fellowship of the Stove

name: limoncello freeze
review: Scrumptious! I was concerned the lemon might be too lollipop, but it was a lovely and delicate and the limoncello came through but wasn't too boozy. I made coconut pecan shortbread cookies and crumbled them on top and I made the limoncello. The cookies were perfect with it, a little crunch is always a good thing!. I used full fat vanilla ice cream and made a smaller serving . Made for SWT2018 A Sweet Taste of Argentina challenge by one of the Pantry Pirates

name: coconut pecan shortbread
review: These are delicious shortbread they're very light and delicate. I cut the recipe in half otherwise made as written except instead of rolling the dough and cutting them out, I shaped it into a log , Chilled, and then sliced the cookies which was very simple. Made for SWT 2018 for of the Pantry Pirates

name: peach oatmeal muffins
review: Wow, these muffins were so good! I had some fresh peaches that were getting very ripe and needed to be used up, so I used them instead of the canned. I used 3 medium which I peeled and diced. Also, I used the King Arthur 100% white whole wheat option. We like lots of spices in our muffins, so I used the higher amounts given in the recipe. They smelled so good while they were baking that we both had to have one shortly after coming out of the oven...delicious! I have 4 peach trees that always seem to get ripe all at the same time. This recipe is one that I will use over and over again to use up the abundance of peaches I have. Thank you for sharing this recipe...it is definitely a keeper! **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: lima beans and mushrooms
review: I had an opened bag of Lima beans in the freezer. I used that and a container of fresh sliced mushrooms. Like with every recipe, extra garlic is a must. We're not huge fans of Lima beans. But, we really enjoyed them like this!

name: easy moist banana blueberry muffins
review: These muffins were a little dry. I used gluten free flour because we have a family member with a gluten intolerance. Next time I will add another banana.

name: lotta lemon muffins
review: Oh man, are these ever yummy! They are very moist and so full of lemon flavor, and tangy too. We are a lemon loving family, and these were a huge hit. The tangy glaze is what makes these muffins so special. I added 1/2 tsp. lemon extract to the batter to give the lemon flavor a boost. Also, I mixed the glaze ingredients in a 1-cup glass measuring cup and microwaved on medium power until the sugar was dissolved and the mixture was simmering. The muffins were done baking and lightly browned after 15 mins. Thank you for sharing this wonderful recipe. It is most definitely a keeper. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: aussie shrimp on the barbie with orange ginger sauce
review: We enjoyed this shrimp dish, it was quick and easy to make. After reading the other review I decide to reserve about half the sauce (there was still plenty to go on the shrimp for grilling) which I reduced in a fairly hot skillet and cooked down till it was fairly thick , this only took a few minutes. I served the grilled shrimp on top of the sauce. I salted and peppered the shrimp before grilling and added a clove a garlic to the sauce which was very flavorful. We really liked the ginger and orange combination. Made for SWT 2018 by one of the Pantry Pirates

name: grilled swordfish  green beans and spicy tomato salsa
review: We loved this simple, yet tasty fish dish. The tomato salsa was the real star of the show. The flavor was very fresh and paired perfectly with the fish. I used 4 plum tomatoes and a cucumber from my garden. Also, I used a garlic infused olive oil for the dressing and for rubbing on the fish. The cooking time was spot on using my bbq grill. This was paired with a Yellow Tail Chardonnay for a perfect dinner. **Made for Susie's World Tour - Australia for the "Australian Food & Wine Pairing" challenge.

name: roasted rosemary chicken with lemon soy sauce
review: Instead of a roast chicken I used boneless chicken breasts. I flattened them slightly so they were an even thickness and marinated them in a mix of the rest of the ingredients for a short time. I then pan grilled them in a little olive oil and poured the little bit of marinade that was left over the top at the beginning of cooking. When they were ready to turn after browning on the first side they had release a lot of liquid which I poured off and save I added a little more oil to the pan and waited for it to heat up before putting the chicken back in to cook on the other side. I was trying to avoid steamed chicken . When the chicken was cooked through there was, a nice frond in the pan so I deglazed with the reserved pan drippings and some chicken broth, I also added some more lemon juice since it was a little subdued. I let this a reduce a bit then whisked in a couple TBLS of cold butter to make a flavorful pan sauce. The lemon, garlic and rosemary were wonderful together, the soy was a hint in the background , I could have used more, but it was great as is. I look forward to trying to this again with a whole chicken but would also be happy making it with just breast again or just chicken thighs. No picture - it wasn't very pretty but super delicious first night and again as left overs.

name: beef bolognese   delish
review: Highly recommended! How does Eva stay a size zero? I made two versions, one with beef and one with veggie crumbles and both were delicious. Will make this one again!

name: skinny dirty brown rice with shrimp
review: So delicious!! I've always wanted to make dirty rice and now I know I'll make it again! I loved the brown rice and all of the different flavours with the veggies and spices and the shrimp? So good! Thanks Jostlori! :)

name: grilled swordfish  green beans and spicy tomato salsa
review: This dish was beautiful, flavorful and delicious. I thought lettuce and green beans were odd to combine but I really enjoyed them together. The salsa was so good the sweetness of the balsamic was a nice balance to the onion. I greatly reduced the red pepper and added more black pepper. My husband loved it as leftovers too!

name: roasted brussels sprouts with bacon
review: Roasting is my favorite way to prepare Brussels sprouts, as it brings out their natural sweetness. Add bacon and garlic, and you have a real winner. Needless to say, we loved this dish! I used garlic infused olive oil and added some fresh, cracked black pepper. Other than that, I made the recipe as written. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018 - Australia**

name: coffee imperial
review: I really like the subtlety of the cinnamon in this drink. I can taste it but it's not overwhelming the dark, strong coffee. I didn't add much sugar to the coffee or the whipped cream but there was a little bit in the cinnamon that I sprinkled on top and it was just right for me. Thanks momaphet! :)

name: cajun spinach dip to die for
review: This dip is creamy and rich with a definite Cajun flavor. It's easy to make and goes together quickly. I should have left out the 1 teaspoon salt, as it was much too salty for our tastes. Unfortunately, the saltiness overpowered the delicious flavor for us. I used a combination of red and orange bell pepper, and I used the half-and-half. I served this with slices of baguette bread. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: cajun kisses
review: I heard the shrimp wouldn't fit so I bought the most humongous jalapenos I could find. Then the shrimp fit, but it did require some extra bacon- not that I am complaining. I did these out on the grill since I was grilling outdoors. Everything was nice. I found the easy way to prep the peppers is to cut off the top and gouge out the seeds with a vegetable peeler (I trick I have been using for a long time now). These were my favorite at dinner! Made for Susie's World Tour.

name: blackeyed peas and cajun sausage
review: Very tasty! I did add extra water as you suggested. I also used a fresh andouille instead of a smoked andouille since it was what I had and it tastes delish.

name: healthy shrimp jambalaya
review: Quick and easy jambalaya that has lots of flavor. I had to make a few changes based on the ingredients I had on hand. I used raw shrimp, so I needed to cook it a bit longer after adding the shrimp to make sure they got done. Also, I used V-8 juice instead of the tomato juice, and I cooked the onion with garlic-infused olive oil. I chose to use the smoked paprika option for added flavor and I'm glad that I did. This dish was delicious! Thank you for sharing. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: creamy cajun deviled eggs
review: Booze, pancakes and deviled eggs are the 3 things that I almost never partake in outside of Tour time, so of course I had to try these. I really liked the filling in these, especially after they chilled and the flavors had a chance to meld. The only change I made was to use dill pickle relish in place of sweet pickle relish. I'll eat just about any kind of pickle EXCEPT sweet pickles, so I only buy dill relish when I need pickle relish. Definitely a keeper IMO! Thanks for posting! Made for SWT2018 Cajun/Creole for Team Fellowship of the Stove

name: green beans in sour cream
review: These beans had lots of flavor even though there were not many ingredients. I used the sour cream option, and cooked the onions in garlic infused olive oil instead of the butter. Also, I added some salt and fresh cracked black pepper. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: broiled fish with dill butter
review: Quick and simple to make, lots of flavor. I increased the dill and cayenne pepper, and made the butter ahead of time and stuck it in the freezer. I used cod fillets, and cooked them in foil on the barbecue grill. I added some salt and fresh cracked black pepper. **Made for Susie's World Tour 2018**

name: beer can chicken
review: Beer can chicken has been a family favorite for years and this version did not disappoint. Cooked on the Traeger with apple wood. Made for Susie's World Tour.

name: garlicky summer squash and fresh corn
review: Tasty and pretty!

name: sausage sauce piquant
review: I was planning to make a shrimp-based dish for the First You Make a Roux challenge, but I didn’t get to the grocery store over the weekend. Poked through the freezer to see what alternate proteins I had on hand, and luckily, I had a big package of chicken Andouille sausage in there. Even hubby didn’t miss the shrimp after he tried this, lol! I liked how easy it was to put together. I also liked that the sauce was so flavorful that the peppers in it tasted good (I don’t love bell peppers, and usually leave them out of everything, but I had a couple of them from the landlord’s garden in my crisper to use up). I also had one small lonely summer squash, so I figured the more veggies, the better — in it went! I gave it a few too many splashes of hot sauce, so it came out pretty spicy, but not so spicy that it overwhelmed the sauce. I couldn’t find where I put my bag of rice, so I went with whole wheat rotini pasta for the starch instead. Thanks for posting this keeper! Made for SWT2018 Cajun/Creole First You Make a Roux challenge for Team Fellowship of the Stove

name: austin sunset
review: I had to make this recipe. For starters, my maiden name is Austin. Plus, earlier this year, I bought a bottle of Aperol, even though I'd never tasted it until tonight. I like things on the sour/bitter side and this drink is perfect in every way. I even like the colour. But be careful. The drink goes down rather easily and it would be easy to overdo it. I limited myself to one.

name: colorful vegetable saute
review: This makes an vegetable side dish. I had everything on hand so made 1/4 of the recipe for two of us. We like sauce so I used half the amount of the white wine and water combo. I added a splash of sesame oil at the very end and then completely forgot to sprinkle over the toasted sesame seeds. Served with Venetian rice (rice, bacon, onion, chicken stock and Parmesan).

name: tangy avocado orange salad
review: Simple and delicious. I garnished with a touch of almonds and dried cranberries. Made for Susie’s World Tour.

name: white chocolate chunk macadamia cookies
review: These are lovely cookies, Sue! They came out nice and chewy, and the combination of add-in’s was perfect together. I’ve been trying to use up some pantry odds-n-ends lately, so I added about 3/4 cup of chopped dried Montmorency cherries that I soaked in hot water beforehand to soften them up. My cookies came out flatter than the ones in the photo, but I chalked that up to my forgetting to add the eggs and vanilla until after I had added the flour — yay, brain cramp! LOL, I was wondering why my dough had suddenly become sandy, more like a cookie crust than cookie dough, and then I looked over at the countertop and realized that the eggs and the bottle of vanilla were just sitting there staring at me. Added the two missing players, mixed the dough again, added the “kibbles and bits” and voila, back on track! I used my medium cookie scoop to portion these out, so I got about 3 1/2 dozen cookies total. I gave a dozen cookies to hubby’s employees, and another dozen to the guys at the Sunoco station who take care of hubby’s landscaping trucks, so lots of people are enjoying your cookies, haha! Thanks for posting! Made for SWT2018 Australia for Team Fellowship of the Stove

name: garlic button mushrooms with breadcrumbs
review: I made half of this recipe for the 2 of us and enjoyed it thoroughly - we could have used more! I love mushrooms and all of the ingredients just enhanced the flavour so much. Don't change a thing - this is perfect! Thanks Karen Elizabeth! :)

name: bacon and tater tots crock pot breakfast
review: From reading reviews I ended up doing 1.5 lbs tater tots and only cooking 4 hours. I also topped with fresh parsley for some color. It's not the prettiest but it tastes great!

name: the very best salisbury steak
review: Pretty good. Made as written.

name: split pea soup  crock pot    dairy free
review: Made as written. Very good. Used broth, not water.

name: lemon pepper chicken breasts on a bed of rice
review: Followed cooking instructions and rice and chicken were perfectly done. It was still a bit bland for me though. Added salt, lemon zest, and parsley to help up the flavor. Then it was much better.

name: light chicken broccoli alfredo soup  lower fat
review: Oh my goodness, AMAZING! I just used regular half and half and Parmesan, not worried about low fat. The whole family loved it, kids devoured it.

name: sweet corn with parmesan and cilantro
review: This is a totally wonderful recipe for sweet corn. I made half a batch which was more than enough to brush/dribble over three smallish ears of corn. Served with fried rice and grilled steaks. Thanks so much for posting.

name: chunky gazpacho
review: Oh my goodness, my search for the perfect gazpacho recipe is over. This is it. Spot on in every way. I didn't bother to blend it, just enjoyed the balance of flavours and the small chunks. Made as written using a red onion and tomato juice. I even peeled and deseeded the tomatoes -- not my favourite kitchen task. Assembled the ingredients at 8am and enjoyed for lunch. By the way, this really only serves 3 to 4. I mean, you have to have a big bowl of it. Yum, yum, yum!

name: horse radish butter  pepperotsmor
review: What a delicious savoury butter. I made half a batch to spread on steaks and baked potatoes. There's still some left over and I might stir that into a veggie soup. Yum, yum, yum! Thanks so much for sharing.

name: orange almond scones
review: I usually find scones to be too dry but not these! The have a nice texture to them and don't crumble. I really enjoyed the flavours of the orange and almond. - they go together nicely. I had this with coffee but not because I needed a drink to wash it down! Thanks momaphet! :)

name: candied  pecans
review: Another winner, Annacia! I usually don’t go out of my way to eat nuts, but I’m a sucker for pralines and candied pecans. I really like the salt with the sweet in the coating here. I only added one tweak: I added the lightest sprinkle of ground cayenne pepper to the coating before adding the pecans. It’s just a hint of something in the flavor, probably not something you could pinpoint and identify if you didn’t know ahead of time, but it’s there, and it’s good! Now I just need them to completely cool off so I can put them away and go to bed before I stand in front of the stove and polish off the whole darn batch myself! Made for SWT 2018 Cajun/Creole for Team Fellowship of the Stove

name: chicken cutlets with mushrooms and pearl onions
review: What a great recipe. I made this with two rather large (and thick) chicken breasts, so cooked the sliced cutlets for 3 minutes each side at the start. Used the full amounts of mushrooms and onions because we love them. As an aside, we can't get frozen pearl onions in Australia, so I used very small eschallots from a neighbour's garden, which took ages to peel but were well worth it. I finished off a bottle of brandy for this recipe, so had just under 1/2 cup, but that was fine. Goes to show you how a recipe like this can be flexible. After I took the photo and put the camera away, I realised I hadn't yet added the thyme. I love this herb and it's a perfect addition. Served over a mixture of brown and white rice, and with steamed broccoli and roasted brussels sprouts. Thanks so much for posting.

name: greek halibut with lemon feta yogurt sauce  rsc
review: I couldn't find fresh halibut so I had to use tilapia. I liked it better without the sauce. DH liked it with the sauce and DD didn't care for it at all.

name: salmon asparagus pie
review: My family doesn't agree on much, but we all agreed that this was pretty bland. Wish I would have read the reviews before making it. Lots of five star reviews, but lots of reviewers tweaked the recipe. That being said, if I ever make it again, I will tweak it too. This recipe is a good base to start with, I just need to jazz it up a bit for my family to eat it.

name: tofu and bok choy stir fry
review: So delicious! I made one-third of a recipe and it served two people.

name: easy baked summer yellow squash
review: My husband, who insists that he does not like squash, ate this. I used garlic salt and gluten free bread crumb because we have a gluten intolerant family member. I also threw in one small zucchini with my three summer squash. Turned out great

name: pan roasted asparagus
review: We are a family of garlic lovers. So, I used extra of course. I also used garlic salt. It was plenty garlicky and we loved every last bite!

name: pasta with sausage  tomatoes  and cream
review: I actually made two separate batches of this for dinnerue to dietary restrictions of family members. The first batch I made with fresh ground mild Italian sausage and gluten free pasta. The second batch was made with whole grain pasta and diced vegetarian Italian sausage. Both times I used a can of no salt diced tomatoes with Italian seasoning, but forgot to drain it when making the first batch. It still turned out fantastic! I also added extra garlic and used garlic salt instead of regular salt. The only suggestion I got from family was one member asked if I could add some more tomatoes next time.

name: baked spaghetti by paula deen
review: Easy to follow directions, and have to agree with Barenakedchef--the angel hair pasta and cheeses should not be substituted with something else. Bottled spaghetti sauce might be an easier shortcut, but Paula's original recipe tastes better.

name: thyme and garlic roasted potatoes  brussels sprouts and carrots
review: I added extra garlic, which is the norm for our garlic loving family. I am not usually a fan of cooked carrots, but I liked them this way. The potatoes were the favorite, followed by the carrots and the brussel Sprouts were the least favorite. Next time I may adjust the amounts of those three main ingredients according to my families preferences..

name: a1 garlic  steak marinade
review: I made this marinade for some ribeye steaks I had in the freezer. While grilling the steaks, I had some portobello mushrooms caps I needed to use up so I threw them on the grill as well. I brushed the marinade on the mushrooms while cooking. Sliced them up and served them as a side to the ribeyes. While my family that the marinade was okay on the steaks, I really enjoyed it more on the mushrooms! What a pleasant surprise!

name: jumbo shrimp parmesan
review: I had to use gluten free bread crumbs due to a family member's gluten intolerance, but otherwise followed the recipe. They turned out great and were enjoyed by all. Served with a side of garlic chive noodles.

name: rib eye steak with spicy cream a1 sauce
review: While DD and I weren't crazy about this sauce, it was to be expected as were not huge fans of A1. My husband, on the other hand, really liked it.

name: velveeta goulash
review: Everyone seemed to like it but DD liked it better without the cheese on top. I used a can of diced tomatoes with basil and oregano in them. I also used a little less tomato paste than the recipe called for.

name: blue cheese stuffed potatoes with buffalo chicken tenders
review: My potatoes took a lot longer to bake than 45 minutes. I used 1% milk in the the lesser amount called for. I also used the reduced fat blue cheese. Once the potatos were restuffed I covered them with foil and put them in the fridge. (The potatoes took so long to bake that my starving family already ate by the time I had reached this point.) The following night I heated the oven back up and popped the potatoes in while making the chicken. I used extra garlic and garlic salt for the salt amount (can you tell we like our garlic here) and the full amount of Anchor Bar wing sauce. The vegetarian in our family just had the stuffed potato with wing sauce drizzled on it. Five stars is hard to get from my family. But everyone really liked these. Even Blue cheese hating DD!

name: dill pickle dip     yum
review: Good dip recipe as is, but it's a little heavy on the mayo flavor. Next time I think I'll try using 1/3 cup mayo and 2/3 cup sour cream.

name: classic raisin oatmeal cookies
review: We really enjoyed these easy, delicious cookies. I thought they were yummy, but I knew the real test was to see what my husband thought of them. Oatmeal raisin cookies are his all-time favorite cookie and when he gave them 2-thumbs up, I knew we had a winner. My first pan out of the oven produced cookies that had spread too much and were very thin. I added a little extra flour to the remaining batter and that did the trick. The rest of the cookies turned out perfect. I got about 3 dozen cookies out of the recipe and a very happy husband. Thank you for sharing this wonderful recipe. **Made for 2018 Football Pool**

name: balsamic marinated steaks
review: DH said this had great flavor. The steaks weren't very think so I only let them marinade 24hrs.

name: red potatoes with butter and chives
review: We had some baby red potatoes and garlic chives in our basket of goodies from the farmers market. A great way to use both. We love garlic so we used the garlic salt and pepper grinder instead of plain table salt. Served as a side to grilled chicken and Italian green beans.

name: thyme marinated grilled asparagus
review: I used extra minced garlic and whole grain garlic mustard because that's what we had on hand and we love our garlic. While we enjoyed the flavor, we all felt it was extremely mild. Next time I will let it marinade longer before putting it on the grill.

name: linguine with sausage and kale
review: I have to admit, I didn't use exact measurements for some ingredients. I used what I had on hand. I used the whole package of sausage, more than double the garlic, a large red pepper and part of a green, a whole onion and half a produce bag of kale from my farm share. I also had to use gluten free Barilla spaghetti due to a family member with gluten intolerance. Some family members added additional Parmesan and one got out the garlic pepper seasoning grinder to give theirs more flavor. But, we all enjoyed it!

name: portabella pizzettas
review: I made these using 3 large portobello caps. They had very short steams. So I just chopped them and added them to the spinach and cheese mixture. I diced grape tomatoes from the garden and sprinkled with garlic salt, omitting the regular salt. They were so good. DH isn't a fan of spinach, so he said he'd prefer if I cut back on it next time. But, all in all, these were a hit.

name: chicken  mushroom  sugar snap peas  and red bell pepper stir fry
review: Made this for my family for dinner. Followed the recipe to a T. My family said it was good but didn't have as much flavor as they had hoped it would. Next time I'll try increasing the garlic and ginger and making more sauce.

name: lemon chive rice
review: I made this using the turmeric option. I also used fresh garlic chives. DD didn't care for it at all, but the rest of us really enjoyed it. Served as a side to the sal on we had for dinner.

name: chile jam chicken
review: Oh my goodness, what a delicious recipe for chicken. A little while ago, a friend gave me a jar of gourmet chile jam that, in my opinion, wasn't all that interesting. I chose this recipe to see if it might be the perfect way to use up this jam. Well. I was right. I used a couple of boneless chicken breasts, and they were perfect. You can be sure this jar of chile jam will be gone in no time. Served with sweet potatoes and wild rice.

name: mashed potatoes with creme fraiche and chives
review: There were just three of us today, so I made 1/3 of a batch. Made mostly as written, using chives from my garden and low-fat milk. Creme fraiche isn’t readily available in Australia, so I used sour cream instead. At first I thought there would be too much liquid, but the quantities were spot on. The guest who joined us for the meal was still enjoying spoonfuls of potatoes as she went out the door to go home. Served with sumac chicken, mushroom casserole and honeyed carrots. Thanks for this brilliant recipe.

name: smoky spicy lime sweet potatoes
review: We are big fans of sweet potatoes and this recipe does them proud. Chipotle powder and sauce are hard (or impossible) to get in Australia, so I used smoked paprika (recommended online as a good substitute). Lime is the perfect addition to this recipe. I will make this often. Thanks so much for posting.

name: roasted garlic mashed sweet potatoes
review: I wanted to serve this today with a slow-cooked beef casserole, so used the orange sweet potatoes I already had on hand. Besides, white sweet potatoes aren’t all that common in Australia. It was for just two of us, so I used 2 medium-sized sweet potatoes, 5 cloves of garlic, 2 tablespoons of butter and 1 1/2 tablespoons of whipping cream. Hubby said, ‘This is so good, what’s that extra added flavour?’ and I knew he meant the roasted garlic. A truly delicious way to make sweet potatoes. Will make often.

name: sauted mushrooms with red wine
review: I didn't have any fresh parsley on hand. So, to save a trip to the store, I used 2 teaspoons of dried parsley. I also used a garlic salt and pepper blend. They turned out fantastic!

name: pumpkin cake bars with cream cheese frosting
review: If you use fresh pumpkin purée instead of canned, l recommend cutting back on the vegetable oil a bit. Other than that, I wouldn't change a thing.

name: cabbage soup with ham
review: Hubby, who eats a granny smith apple every day, loved this soup, but the apple made it just a bit too sweet for me. I did love the way it incorporated four vegetables. That's always a big plus in my book. Also, I needed to add an extra cup or so of water to create enough broth.

name: pizza roll ups
review: Made these for dinner tonight using gluten free pizza dough. Everyone in the family felt they needed more cheese or something, but seemed to like them overall.

name: classic burger sauce
review: This is my Go To recipe. I love it. I tried many other burger sauce recipes and I kept saying to myself 'Well, its not as good as Classic Burger Sauce'. So I have stopped trying other recipes. I am showing this recipe as coming from America's Test Kitchen. After making this recipe more than a dozen times, I found myself using half the amount of Mayo with a Light Mayo and substituting the granulated sugar with a no calorie product such as Splenda. Both of those substitutions worked for me. I was not able to discern a difference in taste. I have also added a couple of tablespoons for finely diced onion, which I think makes it a real Thousand Island dressing. My point is make it as written or tweek it a little. It's all good.

name: fried rice spice
review: This was wonderful. That's my main review, but the tweaks will explain more!

name: creamy au gratin potatoes
review: This recipe was made on 10/28/18 as part of mine and my SO's dinner,but most importantly for the " Autumn Fever " event ;) .Since I love using leftovers the recipe was doubled. I did however change the way it was layered, I placed half of the potatoes in the prepared dish,then salted and peppered them and then topped with the onions.Then poured half of the sauce over the top, added the rest of the potatoes, and sprinkled with more S & P. After adding the remaining sauce the top was sprinkled with a small amount of Paprika. About 10 minutes before the spuds were done , I removed the foil so the top could brown up a bit. The baking time was " SPOT ON " We both thoroughly enjoyed this recipe. I do think however the next time that I make this, I will dice the onions instead of slicing them. Thanks for posting a wonderful recipe, and " Keep Smiling :) "

name: oatmeal peanut butter chocolate chip bars
review: Hi, this recipe was wonderful. I baked mine for 22 min and that seemed just fine.

name: stove top easy chicken bake
review: Tired after working all day and didn't want to run to the store. Only had frozen broccoli and cream of mushroom soup. Still turned out great. Perfect when you are looking for a quick and easy meal.

name: orange dreamsicle
review: What a wonderful memory from my childhood. When I was young, these ice cream bars were called 50/50 bars. They were definitely among my favorite ice cream treats.
